1. 중간고사 답안 작성 및 제출 요령

  • 모든 답안 도출 과정은 R 코드로 작성되어야 하며, 코드에는 분석 과정을 식별할 수 있도록 주석(#)으로 설명이 작성되어야 한다. (R 코드 없이 답만 적는 경우 오답 처리)

  • 수강생 간 코드를 공유하거나 동일하게 작성하는 행위를 금지한다. (적발 시 진실의 방 소환 및 모두 0점으로 성적 반영)

  • 특정한 문제에 대한 답안은 해당 문항에 대한 코드에 작성되어야 한다. (1번 문항에 대한 답을 2번 문항에 적는 경우 오답 처리)

  • 답안은 Rmd 확장자로 보고서 제작이 가능하도록 제출하는 것을 원칙으로 하나, Markdown 실행이 어려운 경우 R 스크립트로 작성하되 채점이 가능하도록 문항 별로 스크립트를 작성하여야 한다.

  • 중간고사 답안은 4월 10일 23시 59분까지 온라인 강의실 내 과제 및 평가 - 중간고사 탭에 제출하여야 하며, 4월 11일 자정 이후에는 제출이 불가하다. (이후 다른 경로를 통하여 제출 시 총점의 50%로 성적 반영)



2. 데이터 설명

어느 의류 생산 공정에서는 재봉 (sewing), 마감 (finishing)으로 부서를 구성하여 공정을 운영하고 있으며, 공정의 생산성을 개선하기 위해 일별 공정 작업 관련 데이터를 수집하여 생산성에 영향을 미치는 요인을 분석하고자 한다. 데이터 분석에 활용하는 변수의 정보는 다음과 같다.

  • date: 집계 날짜
  • quarter: 한 달을 나눈 분기 (주)
  • department: 부서
  • day: 요일
  • team: 부서별 투입 인원 수
  • targeted_productivity: 당초에 목표한 생산성 점수
  • over_time: 초과근무 (분)
  • incentive: 성과급
  • actual_productivity: 실제 생산성 점수


상기에 기술된 작성요령과 데이터를 기반으로 주어진 문제에 대한 분석 과정과 그에 따른 답안을 기술하시오.

#Plotting Data
visualize = function(x, title) {
  if(is.factor(x)) {
    freqs <- table(x)
    Bar <- barplot(freqs, col='navy', main=paste("Barplot of ", "'",title,"'"))
    text(x = Bar, y = freqs + max(freqs) * 0.01, labels = freqs, pos = 1, cex = 1, col='hotpink')
  }
  else {
    H <- hist(x, breaks=12, plot = FALSE)
    plot(H, col='navy', main=paste("Histogram of ", "'", title, "'"))
    mids <- H$mids
    counts <- H$counts
    text(x = mids, y = counts + max(counts) * 0.05, labels = counts, pos = 1, cex = 1, col='hotpink')
  }
}

par(mfrow=c(4,2), mar=c(4, 4, 2, 1), oma=c(1, 1, 1, 1))
for(i in 1:ncol(df)){

}



2. 실제 생산성 점수 (actual_productivity)가 어떠한 분포를 따르는지 규명하기 위하여 여러 분포에 대한 MLE를 추정 및 비교하고, 최적 분포를 도출하시오. (15점)

  • 여러 분포 (최소 2개 이상)에 대하여 MLE를 통하여 모수를 추정할 것
  • 분포별 추정 결과 비교 시 적합도 평가 지표를 활용할 것
  • 추정 결과에 따른 최적 분포를 도출하고, 그 근거를 제시할 것
#Data
x <- df$Actualproductivity

#Distribution Negative Log-likelihood function
gamma_loglikelihood <- function(par, x){
  -sum(dgamma(x, shape=par[1], rate=par[2], log=T))
}

norm_loglikelihood <- function(par, x) {
  -sum(dnorm(x, mean=par[1], sd=par[2], log=T))
}

weib_loglikelihood <- function(par, x){
  -sum(dweibull(x, shape=par[1], scale=par[2], log=T))
}

exp_loglikelihood <- function(par, x){
  -sum(dexp(x, rate=par, log=T))
}

#Optimization MLE function each distribution
res_gamma <- optim(par = c(3, 6), fn = gamma_loglikelihood, x = x, control = list(type = 2))
res_norm <- optim(par = c(mean(x), var(x)), fn = norm_loglikelihood, x = x, control = list(type = 2))
res_weib <- optim(par = c(5, 1), fn = weib_loglikelihood, x = x, control = list(type = 2))
res_exp <- optim(par = 1, fn = exp_loglikelihood, x = x, method="L-BFGS-B", control = list(type = 1))

#Make Table of MLE Estimation and Choose Best Model
num_param <- c(2, 2, 2, 1)
idx <- c("Gamma", "Normal", "Weibull", "Exponential")
ll <- c(res_gamma$value, res_norm$value, res_weib$value, res_exp$value)
AIC <- -2 * ll + 2 * num_param
BIC <- -2 * ll + log(length(x)) * num_param
est <- rbind(res_gamma$par, res_norm$par, res_weib$par, c(res_exp$par, NaN))
Res <- data.frame(
  Log_likelihood = ll,
  AIC = AIC,
  BIC = BIC,
  Estimated_Parameter = est
)
rownames(Res) <- idx

#Print distribution MLE value and parameters
kable(Res, "html") %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover"), full_width = F)

curve(dexp(x, rate=res_exp$par), col='black', add=T)

3. 2. 에서 도출된 최적 분포를 기준으로 MLE 추정 결과를 시각화하고 이를 해석하시오. (10점)

  • 시각화의 경우 실제 데이터의 분포와 MLE를 모수로 가지는 분포의 비교가 가능하도록 도시할 것
  • 단순 도시가 아닌 도시 결과에 대한 해석 결과를 설명하고, 결론을 도출할 것
#Plot and Fit Actual Productivity with Best Distribution (= Weibull)
plot(fitdist(x, "weibull"))

kable(des, "html") %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover"), full_width = F)
Description
Empirical and Theoretical Desnity at the empirical and theoretical distributions, the center and overall shape express the Wyble shape well. However, it is judged that the expression of the center value is a little insufficient and I think that the distribution of values smaller than the center is not well explained.
Q-Q plot Looking at the above distribution fit through the Q-Q (quantile-quantile) plot, the above plats show significant deviations in the lower and upper tail portions, suggesting that the tail portion of the empirical data may not follow the Weibull distribution perfectly.
CDFs Empirical CDFs follow the theoretical curve closely in the middle part, but deviations exist in the lower tail part and in the stepped form of the center. This suggests that the Weibull distribution may be able to represent the data to some extent, but it may not be able to capture the distribution of extreme and central values effectively.
P-P plot Similar to the CDF plot, it typically follows a diagonal but has noticeable deviations, especially in the bottom tail of the probability and in the cascading form of the center.
Suggenstion Based on the previous distribution visual interpretation, I propose a 3-parameter wibble distribution for the fit of the lower tail and the central cascade. Below, we will explain the difference between 2-parameter wibble and 3-parameter wibble. 
#Fitting Data with 3-Parameter Weibull Distribution
weib3_loglikelihood <- function(par, x){
  -sum(FAdist::dweibull3(x, shape=par[1], scale=par[2], thres=par[3], log=T))
}
res_weib3 <- optim(par = c(5, 1, 0), fn = weib3_loglikelihood, x = x, control = list(type = 2))

#Visualization Rationale
hist(x, breaks=15, prob=T, main='3-Param Weibull   vs   2-Param Weibull')
curve(FAdist::dweibull3(x, shape=res_weib3$par[1], scale=res_weib3$par[2], thres=res_weib3$par[3]), add=T, col='red', lwd=3)
curve(dweibull(x, shape=res_weib$par[1], scale=res_weib$par[2]), col='blue', add=T, lwd=3)
legend('topleft', legend = c('3-Parameter', '2-Parameter'), col=c('red', 'blue'), lwd=3)

#Create Table for Comapre with (2-param Weib, 3-param Weib)
weib_param <- c(3, 2)
idx_w <- c("3-Parameter Weibull", "2-Parameter Weibull")
ll_w <- c(res_weib3$value, res_weib$value)
AIC_w <- -2 * ll_w + 2 * weib_param
BIC_w <- -2 * ll_w + log(length(x)) * weib_param
est_w <- rbind(res_weib3$par, c(res_weib$par, NaN))
Res_w <- data.frame(
  Log_likelihood = ll_w,
  AIC = AIC_w,
  BIC = BIC_w,
  Shape = est_w[,1],
  Scale = est_w[,2],
  Threshold = est_w[,3]
)
rownames(Res_w) <- idx_w

kable(Res_w, "html") %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover"), full_width = F)

# Generate Q-Q Plot
qqplot(qweibull(ppoints(length(data)), shape, scale, location), data,
       main = "Q-Q Plot for Weibull Data",
       xlab = "Theoretical Quantiles",
       ylab = "Sample Quantiles")
qqline(data, distribution = function(p) qweibull(p, shape, scale, location), col = "red")

# Generate P-P Plot
ppplot <- function(data, dist, params) {
  theoretical_p <- ppoints(length(data))
  sample_p <- sort(pweibull3(data, params[1], params[2], params[3]))
  plot(theoretical_p, sample_p, main = "P-P Plot",
       xlab = "Theoretical Probabilities", ylab = "Empirical Probabilities")
  abline(0, 1, col = "red")
}
ppplot(data, "weibull", c(shape, scale, location))

Description about Actual Productivity Difference of Each Columns

Columns Description
Quarter Significant differences between actual productivity and target productivity occur from the 3rd quarter. 3rd quarter and 4th quarter actual productivity records lower productivity than target productivity. As a result, in the 5th quarter, actual productivity, which is much higher than target productivity, is recorded due to an increase in supply to meet demand. This is because the target production plan to meet the supply volume is not met in the 3rd and 4th quarters, and the actual productivity that exceeds the target productivity is shown in the 5th quarter.
Department Significant mean differences between departments are not easy to determine. Although it is difficult to judge from the given average and quanatile values alone, the difference between target productivity and actual productivity is larger in the sewing department than in the finishing department. This can be thought to be due to the fact that the sewing department’s process difficulty is higher than that of the finishing department, which increases the reprocessing rate due to the defect rate.
Day The target productivity and actual productivity of each day of the week show the greatest difference on weekends. Friday is designated as a company holiday, and as a result, Saturday after the holiday records actual productivity that exceeds target productivity. This indicates that process efficiency increases significantly after the holidays. Conversely, on Sundays, actual productivity is recorded below target productivity because employees go to work on a day when others do not go to work. Among weekdays, Wednesday shows the biggest difference. It can be thought that this is the result of the aftereffects of working four days in a row on Saturday, Sunday, Monday, and Tuesday.



5. 부서 (department) 별로 실제 생산성 점수 (actual_productivity)의 분포에 차이가 있다고 볼 수 있는지 검정하고자 한다. 신뢰수준 99% 하에서 모평균, 모분산 가설검정을 수행하시오. (10점)

  • 가설검정을 수행할 때에는 5단계의 절차를 준용하여 코드 및 설명을 작성할 것
  • 모평균 검정 시 모분산은 알려지지 않았으며, 부서별 생산성 점수의 모분산은 다르다고 가정
#Population Mean Hypothesis Test
#First-step : Set H0 and H1
cat("H0: Each department's actual productivity distribution of Mean is same.", "\n")
## H0: Each department's actual productivity distribution of Mean is same.
cat("H1: Each department's actual productivity distribution of Mean is significantly different.", "\n")
## H1: Each department's actual productivity distribution of Mean is significantly different.
#Second-step : set Alpha value
alpha <- 0.01

#Actual Productivity Data Split as Department
df_dep <- split(df$Actualproductivity, df$Department)
Sew <- df_dep$sewing
Fin <- df_dep$finishing

#Third step : H0 and H1 is Same / not-same -> Two-Tailed Test
M_res <- t.test(Sew, Fin, var.equal=FALSE, conf.level = 1-alpha) #Diff Variance

#Fourth step : Statistic value
cat("Different variance T-test t value : ", M_res$statistic, "\n")
## Different variance T-test t value :  -3.284567
cat("Different variance estimated mean value : ", M_res$estimate, "\n")
## Different variance estimated mean value :  0.712202 0.7454863
#Fifth step : Test result
cat("Different variance T-test's p-value is larger than alpha(=0.01)?", M_res$p.value > alpha/2, "\n")
## Different variance T-test's p-value is larger than alpha(=0.01)? FALSE
if(M_res$p.value >= alpha/2) {
  print("Choose H0: Each department's actual productivity distribution of Mean is same.")
}
if(M_res$p.value < alpha/2) {
  print("Choose H1: Each department's actual productivity distribution of Mean is significantly different.")
}
## [1] "Choose H1: Each department's actual productivity distribution of Mean is significantly different."
#Population Variance Hypothesis Test
#First step : Set H0 and H1
cat("H0: Each department's actual productivity distribution of Mean is same.", "\n")
## H0: Each department's actual productivity distribution of Mean is same.
cat("H1: Each department's actual productivity distribution of Mean is significantly different.", "\n")
## H1: Each department's actual productivity distribution of Mean is significantly different.
#Second step : set alpha (above this code)

#Third step : H0 and H1 is Same / not-same -> Variance Two-Tailed Test
V_res <- var.test(Sew, Fin, conf.level = 1-alpha)

#Fourth step : Statistic value
cat("Variance-test value : ", V_res$statistic, "\n")
## Variance-test value :  0.5710738
cat("Variance-test estimated value : ", V_res$estimate, "\n")
## Variance-test estimated value :  0.5710738
#Fifth step : Test result
cat("Variance-test's p-value is larger than alpha(=0.01)?",V_res$p.value > alpha/2, "\n")
## Variance-test's p-value is larger than alpha(=0.01)? FALSE
if(V_res$p.value >= alpha/2) {
  print("Choose H0: Each department's actual productivity distribution of Variance is same. \n")
}
if(V_res$p.value < alpha/2) {
  print("Choose H1: Each department's actual productivity distribution of Variance is significantly different. \n")
}
## [1] "Choose H1: Each department's actual productivity distribution of Variance is significantly different. \n"



6. 부서에 따라 목표 생산성 점수 (targeted_productivity) 대비 실제로 달성한 생산성 점수 (actual_productivity)를 초과하는 비율에 차이가 있는지 살펴보고자 한다. 부서 (department) 별로 목표량을 초과하여 생산이 이루어진 비율에 차이가 있는지 95% 신뢰수준 하에서 검정을 수행하고, 달성 비율 차이에 대한 신뢰구간을 산출하시오. (15점)

  • 부서별 전체 데이터 중 목표 생산성 점수가 실제 생산성 점수를 초과하는 비율이 같은지 비교할 것
#Population Proposition Hypothesis Test
#First-step : Set H0 and H1
cat("H0 : Sewing and Finishing Department's Productivity Achievement rate is same.\n")
## H0 : Sewing and Finishing Department's Productivity Achievement rate is same.
cat("H1 : Sewing and Finishing Department's Productivity Achievement rate is different.\n")
## H1 : Sewing and Finishing Department's Productivity Achievement rate is different.
#Second-step : set Alpha 
alpha <- 0.05

#Split data as Department with Target P / Actual P
df_dpt <- split(df$Targetedproductivity/df$Actualproductivity, df$Department)
Sew_dpt <- df_dpt$sewing
Fin_dpt <- df_dpt$finishing

# Target productivity is greater than Actual productivity probability : Productivity Achievement rate
sew_ndat <- length(Sew_dpt)
sew_more_work <- sum(Sew_dpt > 1)
sew_p <- sew_more_work/sew_ndat

fin_ndat <- length(Fin_dpt)
fin_more_work <- sum(Fin_dpt > 1)
fin_p <- fin_more_work/fin_ndat

#Third step : Hypothesis Test (Two-Tailed)
P_res <- prop.test(sew_p, fin_p, conf.level=1-alpha)

#Fourth step : Statistic value
cat("Proposition-test value : ", P_res$statistic, "\n")
## Proposition-test value :  0
cat("Proposition-test estimated value : ", P_res$estimate, "\n")
## Proposition-test estimated value :  0.4939382
#Fifth step : Result
cat("Proposition-test's p-value is larger than alpha(=0.01)?",V_res$p.value > alpha/2, "\n")
## Proposition-test's p-value is larger than alpha(=0.01)? FALSE
if(V_res$p.value >= alpha/2) {
  cat("Choose H0: Each department's productivity acheivement rate is same.\n")
}
if(V_res$p.value < alpha/2) {
  cat("Choose H1: Each department's productivity acheivement rate is different.\n")
}
## Choose H1: Each department's productivity acheivement rate is different.



7. 생산 공정에 투입되는 인원 (team)이 요일 (day)에 관계없이 동일한지 검정하고자 한다. 신뢰수준 95%에서 가설검정을 수행하시오. (15점)

  • 요일별로 평균적인 투입 인원을 산출할 것
  • 실제 투입 인원이 요일에 관계없이 동일한 경우와 비교하여 가설검정을 수행할 것
#First ordered contingency table hypothesis test
#First-step : Set H0 and H1
cat("H0: Regardless Day of Average Team is same.\n")
## H0: Regardless Day of Average Team is same.
cat("H1: Regardless Day of Average Team is different.\n")
## H1: Regardless Day of Average Team is different.
#Second step : Set alpha
alpha <- 0.05

#Data
DayTeam <- table(df$Day, df$Team) #Create Table with Team and Day

#Day Average Team
AvgDay <- c()
for(i in 1:nrow(DayTeam)) {
  AvgDay[i] <- mean(DayTeam[i,]*c(1:12))
}
SameAvg <- rep(mean(AvgDay), length(AvgDay))
Chidat <- rbind(AvgDay, SameAvg)

#Third step : Chi-squared Hypothesis Test
chi_res <- chisq.test(Chidat)

#Fourth step : Statistic value
cat("Chi-squared-test p-value : ", chi_res$p.value, "\n")
## Chi-squared-test p-value :  0.9950345
cat("Chi-squared-test value : ", chi_res$statistic, "\n")
## Chi-squared-test value :  0.410534
cat("Chi-squared-test parameter value : ", chi_res$parameter,"\n")
## Chi-squared-test parameter value :  5
#Fifth step : Result
if(chi_res$p.value < alpha) {
  cat("Choose H1: Regardless Day of Average Team is different.","\n")
} else {
  cat("Choose H0: Regardless Day of Average Team is same.","\n")
}
## Choose H0: Regardless Day of Average Team is same.



8. 초과근무 시간 (over_time)과 성과급 (incentive)이 연관성이 있는지 가설검정을 통하여 확인하고자 한다. 신뢰수준 90%에서 가설검정을 수행하고, 이에 대한 결론을 도출하시오. (15점)

  • 이상치를 배제하기 위하여 인센티브는 80, 초과근무는 8000 미만인 대상만 고려할 것
  • 연속형 변수의 경우, 이산화를 진행하여 변수를 처리해주어야 함
  • 검정을 위한 테이블은 5행 5열로 구성할 것
#Second ordered contingency table hypothesis test
#First-step : Set H0 and H1
cat("H0: There is no correlation with overtime and incentive. \n")
## H0: There is no correlation with overtime and incentive.
cat("H1: There is correlation with overtime and incentive. \n")
## H1: There is correlation with overtime and incentive.
#Load Data EDA
df_SOC <- subset(df, Overtime < 8000 & Incentive < 80)

#Discretize continuous data
Discret <- function(x) {
  cut(x, breaks=5, include.lowest=T)
}

for(col in 1:ncol(df_SOC)) {
  # 연속형 데이터만을 이산화
  if(is.numeric(df_SOC[, col]) || is.integer(df_SOC[, col])) {
    df_SOC[, col] <- Discret(df_SOC[, col])
  }
}

#Create Table
tab_SOC <- table(df_SOC$Incentive, df_SOC$Overtime)
kable(tab_SOC, "html") %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover"), full_width = F)

(15,30] 6 9 20 15 32
(30,45] 8 5 29 27 43
(45,60] 7 4 33 23 51
(60,75.1] 4 3 19 12 19 
#Second step : Set alpha
alpha <- 0.1

#Third step : Chi-squared Hypothesis Test
SOC <- chisq.test(tab_SOC)

#Fourth step : Statistic value
cat("Chi-squared-test value : ", SOC$statistic, "\n")
## Chi-squared-test value :  365.5272
cat("Chi-squared-test parameter value : ", SOC$parameter,"\n")
## Chi-squared-test parameter value :  16
#Fifth step : Result
if(SOC$p.value < alpha) {
  cat("Choose H1: There is correlation with overtime and incentive. \n")
} else {
  cat("Choose H0: There is no correlation with overtime and incentive. \n")
}
## Choose H1: There is correlation with overtime and incentive.
